		<b>Comment By Jenny Shank, 10-08-05</b>
		<p>Thanks for pointing out my typo, Bryan!  I definitely meant "Prairie Schooner" not "Ploughshares"--I guess that prairie/plough imagery confused me.  I do think that Nebraska's "Prairie Schooner" is a fine magazine that ranks up there in quality with "Ploughshares."<br />
<br />
And thanks for the link to Coloradopoetry.org.  I noticed one publication you listed that I should  point out as another regional lit mag that is becoming more and more respected on a national scale--Colorado Review, published by Colorado State University.  The stories it publishes have increasingly been earning honorable mentions in national anthologies like "Prize Stories: The O. Henry Awards" and the Best American Short Stories series.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Bryan Roth, 10-09-05</b>
		<p>I'd agree with you, Jenny, about the Colorado Review, although I must point out that it's been respected on a national level for some time now: we'd even heard of it back in Indiana where I went to college--longer ago than I care to admit in print! The Denver Quarterly has also had national stature for some time. A couple of new magazines, "divide" out of CU-Boulder, "Shiny," and "Elixir," both independent journals out of Denver, and "Matter" out of Ft. Collins, are promising up-and-comers. A couple of other interesting independent journals Colorado poetry lovers would be well-served to check out are "Mad Blood" and "Many Mountains Moving," the latter a truly unique, and quite beautifully produced publication that has been around some ten years already and which has published some of the very best poets (and fiction writers) in the country. Also in Ft. Collins (a literary hotbed!) is the "Front Range Review," a modest publication which publishes some very good poetry. And watch out in the future for "Elevation"--I just happen to have some inside information on that one, and I can tell you it will be a force to be reckoned with on a national scale! And as always, I would encourage everyone who loves poetry to support your local (and state) literary publications by buying a copy now and then. If everyone who reads poetry bought one journal a month, it would make a great difference to those publications, most of which are on very tight budgets with over-worked, volunteer staffs.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Michael Shay, 10-12-05</b>
		<p>As literature coordinator for the Wyoming Arts Council, I was on the first planning committee for the Rocky Mountain Book Festival in 1992-93. The goal, early on, was to make it a regional event and not just a Denver or Colorado bookfest. I worked with other lit coordinators at state arts agencies in Utah, Idaho, and Colorado, back when it had a great Arts Council organizer in Danny Salazar. We partially succeeded, luring poets and writers from these states, sometimes with Arts Council funding. Later, in '95 or '96, the Western States Arts Federation in Denver helped bring in those writers who were part of an anthology for the Tumblewords Audience Development Project. Those mid-90s bookfests at Currigan were raucous affairs, with tons of local schoolkids, a neat book fair, and poetry readings competing with cappuccino machines. Little-known literary writers hob-nobbed (and argued) with those on best-seller lists. Those bookfests were fun, full of energy, and well-organized by the Colorado Center for the Book's committee. When I attended the 2001 version at the Merchandise Mart, the bridal fair next door drew tons of people while tumbleweeds blew through the cavernous bookfest space. I lost track of the event when it was moved yet again. We've now formed a committee for an October 2006 Wyoming Book Festival in Casper. The RMBF is proving to be a case study in how poor planning, schedule-changing, venue-hopping, and lack of focus can destroy a great event.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Jenny Shank, 10-12-05</b>
		<p>So there <i>were</i> some glory days for Denver's sad book festival after all!  It sounds like I'll have to make a pilgrimage to Casper next fall.</p>
		
